    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The probability mass function of the negative binomial distribution is"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "formulas": [
            "P(N;n,p) = \\frac{\\Gamma(N+n)}{N!\\Gamma(n)}p^{n}(1-p)^{N},"
          ],
          "type": "math_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "where "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the number of successes, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "p"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the\nprobability of success, "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "N+n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the number of trials, and\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "\\Gamma"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is the gamma function. When "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " is an integer,\n"
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "\\frac{\\Gamma(N+n)}{N!\\Gamma(n)} = \\binom{N+n-1}{N}"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": ", which is\nthe more common form of this term in the pmf. The negative\nbinomial distribution gives the probability of N failures given n\nsuccesses, with a success on the last trial."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "If one throws a die repeatedly until the third time a \"1\" appears,\nthen the probability distribution of the number of non-\"1\"s that\nappear before the third \"1\" is a negative binomial distribution."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
